{
  "The axial skeleton contains approximately how many bones?": "",
  "60": "",
  "80": "",
  "126": "",
  "206": "",
  "The axial skeleton consists of approximately 80 bones, including those of the skull, vertebral column, and thoracic cage (sternum and ribs).": "",
  "How many cranial bones are there?": "",
  "6": "",
  "14": "",
  "8": "",
  "22": "",
  "There are 8 cranial bones (frontal, two parietal, occipital, two temporal, sphenoid, and ethmoid) that together form the protective braincase known as the cranium.": "",
  "The mandible is the:": "",
  "Upper jaw bone that articulates with the frontal bone above": "",
  "Nasal bone that forms the rigid bridge of the nose": "",
  "Cheekbone forming the lateral zygomatic arch structure": "",
  "Lower jaw and the only movable skull bone": "",
  "The mandible is the lower jaw and the only freely movable bone of the skull, articulating with the temporal bones at the temporomandibular joints (TMJ) to allow chewing and speech.": "",
  "How many cervical vertebrae are in the human spine?": "",
  "5": "",
  "12": "",
  "4": "",
  "7": "",
  "There are always 7 cervical vertebrae (C1-C7) in the human neck, a number that is remarkably consistent across nearly all mammals.": "",
  "C1 (the first cervical vertebra) is called the:": "",
  "Sacrum": "",
  "Coccyx": "",
  "Atlas": "",
  "Axis": "",
  "C1 is called the atlas, named after the Greek Titan who held up the world, because it supports the skull. It has a unique ring shape with no vertebral body and allows the nodding (yes) motion of the head.": "",
  "How many thoracic vertebrae are there?": "",
  "10": "",
  "There are 12 thoracic vertebrae (T1-T12), each articulating with a pair of ribs. This number matches the 12 pairs of ribs in the thoracic cage.": "",
  "The sacrum is formed by how many fused vertebrae?": "",
  "3": "",
  "The sacrum is formed by the fusion of 5 sacral vertebrae, creating a single triangular bone that forms the posterior wall of the pelvis and connects the spine to the hip bones.": "",
  "How many pairs of true ribs are there?": "",
  "Ribs 1 through 7 are true ribs (vertebrosternal ribs) because they each attach directly to the sternum via their own individual costal cartilage.": "",
  "The foramen magnum is located in which cranial bone?": "",
  "Sphenoid bone": "",
  "Occipital bone": "",
  "Frontal bone": "",
  "Temporal bone": "",
  "The foramen magnum is the large opening in the occipital bone at the base of the skull through which the spinal cord passes to connect with the brainstem.": "",
  "The sternum consists of how many parts?": "",
  "One piece: a single fused cartilaginous sternal plate": "",
  "Two parts: the superior manubrium and the inferior body": "",
  "Four parts: manubrium, superior body, inferior body, and xiphoid": "",
  "Three parts: manubrium, body, and xiphoid process": "",
  "The sternum is composed of three fused sections: the manubrium (superior portion), the body (largest middle section), and the xiphoid process (small, inferior cartilaginous tip).": "",
  "What is the atlas (C1)?": "",
  "The second cervical vertebra that has a dens for rotation": "",
  "The uppermost thoracic vertebra": "",
  "The bone that forms the base of the sacrum": "",
  "The first cervical vertebra, a ring-shaped bone that supports the skull and allows nodding": "",
  "The atlas (C1) is the first cervical vertebra, unique for its ring-like shape without a vertebral body. It articulates with the occipital condyles of the skull, allowing the flexion and extension (nodding) movement of the head.": "",
  "What is the axis (C2)?": "",
  "The second cervical vertebra with a dens (odontoid process) that allows rotational head movement": "",
  "A thoracic vertebra that articulates with the first rib": "",
  "The first cervical vertebra that supports the skull": "",
  "The lowest cervical vertebra at the base of the neck": "",
  "The axis (C2) is the second cervical vertebra, characterized by the dens (odontoid process) that projects upward into the atlas. The atlas rotates around the dens, allowing the head to turn side to side (saying 'no').": "",
  "What is the foramen magnum?": "",
  "A small opening in the sphenoid bone for cranial nerves": "",
  "The large opening in the occipital bone through which the spinal cord passes": "",
  "The hole in the hip bone for blood vessels": "",
  "The opening in each vertebra that forms the spinal canal": "",
  "The foramen magnum (Latin for 'great hole') is the largest opening in the skull, located in the occipital bone. It serves as the passage for the spinal cord, vertebral arteries, and the meninges connecting the brain to the spinal cord.": "",
  "What does scoliosis mean?": "",
  "A normal curvature that develops during aging": "",
  "An abnormal lateral (side-to-side) curvature of the spine": "",
  "An excessive forward curvature of the lumbar spine": "",
  "An excessive backward curvature of the thoracic spine": "",
  "Scoliosis is an abnormal lateral curvature of the spine, typically appearing as a C-shaped or S-shaped deviation when viewed from the posterior. It is most commonly diagnosed during adolescence.": "",
  "What is the manubrium?": "",
  "The superior portion of the sternum that articulates with the clavicles and the first pair of ribs": "",
  "The inferior cartilaginous tip of the sternum": "",
  "A process on the scapula": "",
  "The middle and largest section of the sternum": "",
  "The manubrium is the broad, superior portion of the sternum. It articulates with the clavicles at the sternoclavicular joints and with the first pair of ribs, forming the jugular (suprasternal) notch at its superior border.": "",
  "What does costal cartilage mean?": "",
  "The articular cartilage of the shoulder joint": "",
  "The bone tissue that makes up the rib shaft": "",
  "The hyaline cartilage that connects the ribs to the sternum": "",
  "The fibrous tissue between vertebrae": "",
  "Costal cartilage is hyaline cartilage that extends from the anterior end of each rib to the sternum (in the case of true ribs) or to the cartilage above (in false ribs), providing flexible, elastic connections.": "",
  "What is the intervertebral disc?": "",
  "A ligament that connects the spinous processes of vertebrae": "",
  "A bony projection on each vertebra": "",
  "A fibrocartilaginous pad between adjacent vertebral bodies that absorbs shock and allows flexibility": "",
  "The space within the vertebral foramen": "",
  "Intervertebral discs are fibrocartilaginous structures located between adjacent vertebral bodies. Each disc has a tough outer annulus fibrosus and a gel-like inner nucleus pulposus that together absorb shock and allow spinal flexibility.": "",
  "What does kyphosis mean?": "",
  "An excessive anterior curvature of the lumbar spine": "",
  "A fracture of the vertebral body": "",
  "An abnormal lateral curvature of the spine": "",
  "An excessive posterior curvature of the thoracic spine (hunchback)": "",
  "Kyphosis refers to an exaggerated posterior curvature of the thoracic region, commonly known as hunchback or dowager's hump. It can result from poor posture, osteoporosis, or vertebral compression fractures.": "",
  "What does lordosis mean?": "",
  "An excessive posterior curvature of the thoracic spine": "",
  "A condition where vertebrae fail to fuse": "",
  "An excessive anterior curvature of the lumbar spine (swayback)": "",
  "Lordosis is an exaggerated inward (anterior) curvature of the lumbar spine, commonly known as swayback. It can result from obesity, pregnancy, poor posture, or weakness of the abdominal muscles.": "",
  "What are floating ribs?": "",
  "Ribs 8 through 10 that attach indirectly to the sternum": "",
  "Ribs 11 and 12 that have no anterior attachment to the sternum": "",
  "Extra ribs that develop in some individuals": "",
  "Ribs 1 through 7 that attach directly to the sternum": "",
  "Floating ribs are the last two pairs of ribs (11 and 12) that do not attach to the sternum at all, either directly or indirectly. They articulate only with the thoracic vertebrae posteriorly and are embedded in the muscles of the body wall.": "",
  "A patient arrives at the emergency department after a car accident. A CT scan reveals a fracture through the dens (odontoid process) of the C2 vertebra. Why is this injury considered life-threatening?": "",
  "C2 is the only vertebra that supports the ribs": "",
  "C2 fractures always cause immediate hemorrhage into the brain": "",
  "The dens of C2 is adjacent to the spinal cord at a level that controls breathing and vital functions, so displacement can cause paralysis or death": "",
  "C2 carries the vertebral arteries that supply the entire body": "",
  "A fracture of the dens of C2 is dangerous because the dens sits immediately adjacent to the spinal cord at the level of the upper cervical spine. Displacement can compress the spinal cord, potentially causing respiratory arrest, quadriplegia, or death.": "",
  "A school nurse performs scoliosis screenings on middle school students. During one exam, she notices that a student's spine curves laterally when the student bends forward. What should the nurse recommend?": "",
  "Referral to a physician for further evaluation with imaging to confirm scoliosis and determine severity": "",
  "No follow-up is needed since lateral curvature during bending is normal": "",
  "A back brace to be worn only during physical education class": "",
  "Immediate surgery to correct the curvature": "",
  "A visible lateral curvature on the Adams forward bend test is a positive screening finding for scoliosis. The student should be referred for physician evaluation and imaging (typically X-ray) to confirm the diagnosis and measure the degree of curvature.": "",
  "An elderly woman presents with increasing upper back curvature and height loss. X-rays show multiple compression fractures in her thoracic vertebrae. Which condition of the axial skeleton best describes her spinal deformity?": "",
  "Spina bifida caused by incomplete vertebral arch closure": "",
  "Scoliosis resulting from abnormal lateral spinal deviation": "",
  "Lordosis from excessive anterior lumbar spine curvature": "",
  "Kyphosis caused by vertebral compression fractures": "",
  "Kyphosis is an exaggerated posterior curvature of the thoracic spine. In elderly patients, especially postmenopausal women with osteoporosis, compression fractures of the thoracic vertebrae cause progressive kyphosis and loss of height.": "",
  "A boxer takes a hard punch to the jaw and is unable to open his mouth properly afterward. The ringside physician suspects an injury to the only movable joint of the skull. Which structure is most likely affected?": "",
  "The temporomandibular joint (TMJ), where the mandible articulates with the temporal bone": "",
  "The zygomatic arch": "",
  "The coronal suture between the frontal and parietal bones": "",
  "The maxillary bone suture": "",
  "The temporomandibular joint (TMJ) is the only freely movable joint in the skull, connecting the mandible to the temporal bone. Trauma to the jaw can cause TMJ dislocation, fracture, or disc displacement, resulting in difficulty opening the mouth.": "",
  "A patient is receiving CPR. During chest compressions, the rescuer must avoid pressing on the small, cartilaginous inferior tip of the sternum. What is this structure, and why must it be avoided?": "",
  "The manubrium; pressing on it blocks airflow to the lungs": "",
  "The costal margin; pressing there fractures the floating ribs": "",
  "The sternal body; it is too fragile to withstand compression": "",
  "The xiphoid process; applying force to it can fracture it and lacerate the liver": "",
  "The xiphoid process is the small, cartilaginous inferior tip of the sternum. During CPR, it must be avoided because applying pressure to it can fracture or displace it into the underlying liver, causing dangerous internal hemorrhage.": "",
  "A neurosurgeon is operating on a tumor at the base of the skull. She identifies a butterfly-shaped bone that forms part of the middle cranial fossa and houses the sella turcica, which holds the pituitary gland. Which bone is she working near?": "",
  "The occipital bone": "",
  "The frontal bone": "",
  "The sphenoid bone": "",
  "The ethmoid bone": "",
  "The sphenoid bone is a butterfly-shaped bone in the cranial floor that articulates with nearly every other cranial bone. It contains the sella turcica ('Turkish saddle'), the depression that houses and protects the pituitary gland.": "",
  "A young athlete falls while snowboarding and fractures ribs 11 and 12 on the left side. The emergency physician notes that these ribs are particularly vulnerable because they lack a certain attachment. What makes these ribs different?": "",
  "They are the longest ribs and bear the most stress": "",
  "They are floating ribs with no anterior attachment to the sternum, making them less stabilized and more prone to fracture": "",
  "They lack a posterior vertebral attachment": "",
  "They are the only ribs made entirely of cartilage": "",
  "Ribs 11 and 12 are floating ribs that attach only to the vertebrae posteriorly and have no anterior connection to the sternum. This lack of anterior stabilization can make them more susceptible to fracture from direct trauma.": "",
  "A pregnant woman in her third trimester complains of significant lower back pain. Her physician explains that her lumbar curvature has increased due to the weight of the pregnancy. What is this exaggerated curvature called?": "",
  "Spinal stenosis": "",
  "Lordosis": "",
  "Scoliosis": "",
  "Kyphosis": "",
  "The exaggerated anterior curvature of the lumbar spine is called lordosis. During pregnancy, the growing uterus shifts the center of gravity forward, causing the lumbar spine to compensate with increased lordotic curvature, often resulting in back pain.": "",
  "A patient involved in a high-speed collision presents with severe neck pain. Imaging reveals that the atlas (C1) has burst into multiple fragments. The trauma surgeon explains that the vertebral column formula is 7-12-5-5-4. A medical student asks what these numbers represent. What is the correct answer?": "",
  "The number of vertebrae in the cervical, thoracic, lumbar, sacral, and coccygeal regions respectively": "",
  "The number of spinal nerves exiting each region": "",
  "The number of normal curvatures in each region": "",
  "The number of intervertebral discs in each region": "",
  "The vertebral column formula 7-12-5-5-4 represents the number of vertebrae in each spinal region: 7 cervical, 12 thoracic, 5 lumbar, 5 sacral (fused into the sacrum), and approximately 4 coccygeal (fused into the coccyx).": "",
  "A medical examiner is studying a skull and needs to identify a bone that contributes to the nasal septum, forms part of the roof of the nasal cavity, and has a distinctive cribriform plate with tiny perforations. Which axial skeleton bone is being described?": "",
  "The vomer": "",
  "The palatine bone": "",
  "The ethmoid bone is a delicate bone between the orbits that contributes to the nasal septum, forms the roof of the nasal cavity, and features the cribriform plate with tiny holes (foramina) through which olfactory nerve fibers pass from the nasal cavity to the brain.": ""
}